%98You%20don%E2%80%99t%20need%20to%2C%20it%E2%80%99s%20not%20good.%20Let%E2%80%99s%20forget%20everything.%E2%80%99%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fblockquote%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ERon%20kept%20trying%3A%20%E2%80%9CIt%20took%20a%20few%20years%20for%20us%20to%20talk%20about%20it.%20And%20then%20he%20agreed%20for%20me%20to%20do%20it.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EHe%20gave%20the%20tattoo%20artist%20a%20photo%20of%20his%20father%E2%80%99s%20number.%20He%20wanted%20to%20replicate%20it%20as%20closely%20as%20possible.%20He%20wanted%20people%20to%20ask%20about%20it%2C%20to%20keep%20the%20Holocaust%20in%20living%20memory.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20Ron%E2%80%99s%20mind%2C%20this%20replicated%20number%20represents%20continuity.%20It%20ensures%20there%20are%20still%20people%20%E2%80%9Cwalking%20with%20the%20number%E2%80%9D.%20He%20says%20he%20wanted%20to%20experience%20what%20his%20father%20had%20experienced%20when%20his%20name%20was%20taken%20away.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESimilarly%2C%20Rony%20Cohen%20says%20that%20deciding%20to%20replicate%20her%20grandmother%E2%80%99s%20tattoo%20was%20so%20%E2%80%9Cshe%20could%20walk%20with%20me%20for%20good%20%E2%80%93%20it%E2%80%99s%20a%20statement%20for%20me%E2%80%9D.%20Cohen%20too%20wanted%20it%20in%20the%20same%20place%20as%20the%20original%2C%20so%20that%20everyone%20understood%20its%20meaning.%20She%20sees%20her%20body%20as%20becoming%20a%20conduit%20for%20her%20grandmother%20%E2%80%93%20a%20means%20to%20keep%20her%20legacy%20and%20life%20with%20her%20at%20all%20times.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20contrast%20to%20Ron%2C%20though%2C%20Cohen%20did%20not%20broach%20the%20subject%20with%20her%20grandmother.%20She%20just%20went%20ahead%20and%20got%20the%20tattoo%2C%20then%20wore%20long%20sleeves%20at%20family%20gatherings%20%E2%80%93%20much%20like%20some%20survivors%20had%20in%20previous%20decades.%20But%20for%20her%2C%20covering%20the%20tattoo%20wasn%E2%80%99t%20because%20of%20stigma.%20Rather%2C%20she%20worried%20about%20the%20reactions%20it%20might%20trigger.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EEventually%2C%20Cohen%20decided%20to%20show%20the%20number%20to%20her%20grandmother.%20She%20videoed%20her%20response.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAt%20first%2C%20her%20grandmother%20asks%20why%20Cohen%20has%20done%20it.%20Then%20she%20asks%20if%20it%20hurt.%20%E2%80%9CI%20don%E2%80%99t%20want%20you%20to%20do%20something%20that%20hurts%2C%E2%80%9D%20she%20says.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9CNo%20it%20didn%E2%80%99t%2C%E2%80%9D%20Cohen%20replies.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ETo%20which%20her%20grandmother%20asks%3A%20%E2%80%9CWhy%3F%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ECohen%20is%20very%20clear%20that%20getting%20her%20tattoo%20was%20a%20personal%20act%2C%20a%20decision%20relating%20to%20her%20own%20history%2C%20not%20to%20a%20larger%20historical%20one.%20%E2%80%9CI%E2%80%99m%20not%20a%20monument%2C%E2%80%9D%20she%20says.%20%E2%80%9CI%20don%E2%80%99t%20carry%20the%20Jewish%20nation%20on%20my%20back.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EWhen%20the%20Holocaust%20passes%20out%20of%20living%20memory%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMuseums%20and%20memorials%20all%20over%20the%20world%20are%20dedicated%20to%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Fwhy-we-still-need-to-teach-young-people-about-the-holocaust-90481%5C%22%3Etelling%20the%20story%3C%2Fa%3E%20of%20the%20Holocaust.%20Since%202006%2C%20International%20Holocaust%20Remembrance%20Day%20has%20been%20marked%20every%20year%20on%20January%2027.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBut%20despite%20the%20proliferation%20of%20Holocaust-related%20art%20and%20culture%2C%20despite%20the%20books%20laying%20out%20the%20facts%2C%20research%20shows%20many%20people%20are%20ignorant%20of%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.pewresearch.org%2Freligion%2F2020%2F01%2F22%2Fwhat-americans-know-about-the-holocaust%2F%5C%22%3Ewhat%20happened%3C%2Fa%3E.%20In%202021%2C%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22http%3A%2F%2Fwww.claimscon.org%2Fuk-study%2F%5C%22%3Eglobal%20Holocaust%20Awareness%3C%2Fa%3E%20Survey%20found%20large%20gaps%20in%20people%E2%80%99s%20knowledge.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20the%20UK%2C%2052%25%20of%20respondents%20could%20not%20specify%20that%20six%20million%20Jewish%20people%20had%20been%20murdered%20%E2%80%93%20a%20number%20which%20rose%20to%2056%25%20in%20Austria%20and%2057%25%20in%20France.%20Of%20the%20adults%20surveyed%20in%20the%20US%20and%20Canada%2C%2045%25%20and%2049%25%2C%20respectively%2C%20were%20unable%20to%20name%20a%20concentration%20camp%20or%20a%20ghetto.%20Among%20millennials%20in%20the%20US%2C%20only%2049%25%20could%20name%20a%20concentration%20camp%20or%20ghetto.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThis%20matters%20because%2C%20as%20we%20reach%20the%2079th%20anniversary%20of%20the%20liberation%20of%20Auschwitz%20on%20January%2027%201945%2C%20there%20are%20very%20few%20survivors%20left%20to%20give%20a%20first-hand%20account%20of%20what%20was%20done%20to%20them.%20The%20Holocaust%20is%20passing%20out%20of%20living%20memory.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EFor%20those%20whose%20family%20history%20is%20tied%20up%20with%20the%20Holocaust%2C%20memorialising%20it%20is%20both%20public%20and%20private.%20The%20tattoo%20replicating%20the%20Auschwitz%20number%20is%20a%20form%20of%20memorial%20practice%20that%20speaks%2C%20viscerally%2C%20to%20their%20own%20family%20history%20%E2%80%93%20but%20also%20to%20the%20imperative%20to%20never%20forget.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EI%20spoke%20with%20David%20Rubin%20in%20the%20summer%20of%202022.%20He%20bears%20his%20grandmother%E2%80%99s%20number%20on%20his%20arm%2C%20the%20number%20depicted%20as%20if%20written%20on%20a%20piece%20of%20wood%20alongside%20a%20Star%20of%20David%2C%20a%20thorny%20vine%20of%20lilac-coloured%20flowers%20entwined%20around%20it.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EFour%20of%20the%20flowers%20are%20open%2C%20representing%20his%20grandmother%2C%20Piroska%20%E2%80%9CPerl%E2%80%9D%20Levy%2C%20and%20her%20surviving%20sisters.%20To%20the%20left%20lie%20two%20closed%20flowers%2C%20for%20her%20two%20sisters%20who%20were%20killed.%20A%20lone%20flower%20completes%20the%20floral%20framing%20at%20the%20bottom%2C%20in%20memory%20of%20her%20brother%2C%20also%20killed.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ETo%20Rubin%E2%80%99s%20mind%2C%20his%20generation%20is%20probably%20the%20last%20to%20speak%20about%20this.%20Getting%20the%20tattoo%20was%20a%20means%20of%20ensuring%20that%20the%20fourth%20generation%20%E2%80%93%20his%20children%2C%20his%20grandmother%E2%80%99s%20great-grandchildren%20%E2%80%93%20will%20know%20what%20happened.%20%E2%80%9CI%20wanted%20a%20story%2C%20instead%20of%20just%20a%20number%2C%E2%80%9D%20he%20says.%20The%20barbed%20wire%20has%20become%20the%20thorny%20vine%20in%20flower.%20%E2%80%9CIt%E2%80%99s%20taking%20the%20bad%20thing%20and%20%5Bre%5Dcreating%20it%20as%20a%20good%20thing.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMemorial%20tattoos%20are%20a%20way%20of%20expressing%20a%20life%20story.%20They%20are%20an%20external%20scar%20that%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1080%2F07481187.2021.1983889%5C%22%3Eembodies%3C%2Fa%3E%20an%20internal%20one.%20The%20writer%20Eva%20Hoffman%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.penguin.co.uk%2Fbooks%2F358115%2Fafter-such-knowledge-by-eva-hoffman%2F9780099464723%5C%22%3Enotes%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20even%20where%20there%20are%20silences%20in%20how%20families%2C%20including%20her%20own%2C%20reckon%20with%20their%20traumatic%20past%2C%20the%20%E2%80%9Clanguage%20of%20the%20body%E2%80%9D%20still%20breaches%20those%20silences.%20It%20keeps%20the%20unspoken%20past%20ever%20present.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWhile%20descendants%20of%20Holocaust%20survivors%20did%20not%20experience%20the%20trauma%20directly%2C%20the%20intergenerational%20trauma%20is%20long-lasting.%20Rony%20Cohen%20was%20not%20the%20only%20grandchild%20of%20a%20survivor%20who%20told%20me%20they%20dream%20or%20have%20nightmares%20about%20the%20Holocaust.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20doing%20these%20interviews%2C%20I%20have%20found%20that%20replicating%20the%20Auschwitz%20tattoo%20is%20an%20expression%20of%20the%20love%20felt%20towards%20the%20survivor%20relative%2C%20and%20a%20way%20of%20keeping%20the%20memory%20of%20the%20Holocaust%20alive.%20It%20is%20an%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthesociologicalreview.org%2Fpodcasts%2Fthe-stigma-conversations%2Ftattooing-and-resistance-with-alice-bloch%2F%5C%22%3Eact%20of%20reclaiming%3C%2Fa%3E%20a%20painful%20family%20history.%20And%20for%20some%2C%20it%20is%20about%20connections%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Ffrom-the-manchester-bee-to-the-pompey-dot-the-psychology-of-regional-tattoos-198695%5C%22%3Eto%20a%20collective%20identity%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20this%20way%2C%20it%20is%20about%20the%20future%20too.%20When%20there%20are%20no%20more%20survivors%20to%20share%20their%20stories%2C%20these%20descendants%20who%20bear%20on%20their%20living%20bodies%20the%20numbers%20once%20forcibly%20tattooed%20on%20their%20relatives%20will%20stand%20as%20a%20living%20reminder%20of%20where%20racism%20and%20hatred%20can%20lead.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Fprofiles%2Falice-bloch-1451307%5C%22%3EAlice%20Bloch%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20Professor%20of%20Sociology%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Finstitutions%2Funiversity-of-manchester-1204%5C%22%3EUniversity%20of%20Manchester%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3EThis%20article%20is%20republished%20from%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%5C%22%3EThe%20Conversation%3C%2Fa%3E%20under%20a%20Creative%20Commons%20license.%20Read%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Fdescendants-of-holocaust-survivors-explain-why-they-are-replicating-auschwitz-tattoos-on-their-own-bodies-206821%5C%22%3Eoriginal%20article%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1706524229000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F01%2F29152947%2FScreenshot-2024-01-29-at-3.27.08-PM.png%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fhistory%2Fdescendants-of-holocau